description.plain:
Logic is an American rapper hailing from Gaithersburg, Maryland. He has amassed a large internet following and is a member of the RattPack, which stands for Real All The Time and his group of friends that he works with.

He is currently signed with Visionary Music Group and was cosigned to Def Jam Recordings in 2012 by No I.D.

In 2009, Logic unofficially released his first mixtape, Psychological: The Mixtape under the artist name “Psychological,” which was sold locally in Gaithersburg. Since then, he’s released six additional mixtapes and seven studio albums.

As a young rapper, Logic drew influence from Wu-Tang Clan and took inspiration from RZA who produced music for Kill Bill Vol: 1, the film that got him inspired to rap. Another key inspiration for Logic was Frank Sinatra, as Logic developed the alter ego ‘Young Sinatra’ and released his first eponymous mixtape in 2011. He went by various names such as Hitman, East Koast Killa, Lord Subliminal, and Skittles before deciding on “Psychological” but then cut it down to just “Logic” so it was easier for people to say.

In 2013, he was voted as one of XXL’s freshmen of the year, alongside notable rapper ScHoolboy Q.

In 2014, Logic released his debut studio album, Under Pressure under his label Def Jam, which fully dives into his childhood stories, such as gang violence, parent separation issues, and his journey to becoming the best.

In 2017, Logic started his own record label, Team Elysium, which was renamed to Bobby Boy Records in 2019. Founding members include Big Lenbo, Damian Lemar Hudson, and John Lindahl. Logic said the label was made because:

I don’t trust anybody else with the precious cargo that is my family.

In 2018, Logic released two musical projects, Bobby Tarantino II and YSIV, revealed his plans on making a movie, and admitted to writing two novels, one titled Supermarket, which released in 2019 and shortly after became a New York Times Bestseller. It was also accompanied by a soundtrack of the same name.

In May 2019, Logic released his sixth studio album, Confessions of A Dangerous Mind, which includes several collaborations with artists such as Eminem, G-Eazy, Will Smith, and Wiz Khalifa.

In July 2020, Logic announced he will be retiring with the release of his album No Pressure, a sequel to his first album Under Pressure.

On June 16, 2021 Logic announced his return to the music industry  under his stage name and released “Intro” just over a day later.

On July 30th, 2021, Logic released his seventh studio album Bobby Tarantino III, marking his first album out of retirement, and completing the Bobby Tarantino album trilogy.

description.plain:
On “1-800-273-8255,” Logic shows that suicide is never the answer to anyone’s problems. He wants people to know that there is always help available, such as the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline, whose phone number is the title of this song. In fact, the song was released in partnership with the NSPL.

In an interview with Genius, Logic said that this song details the story of someone calling the NSPL wanting to commit suicide but after a conversation with the NSPL representative,  the caller soon after decides he wants to live.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SOJTg9cL5bM

Logic teased the song various times on both Twitter and on Instagram stories as well.

songs.title: Homicide

description.plain:
“Homicide" is the third single released from Logic’s 2019 album, Confessions of a Dangerous Mind.

The track exhibits Logic and Eminem’s rapid-fire flows. The title seems to assert that they are lyrically murdering their detractors and non-lyrical rappers.

In a 2018 interview with HardKnockTV, Logic shared his thoughts on Eminem and his desire to collaborate with him:

It was awesome […] to be recognized by one of my favorite MCs of all time, one of my favorite artists […] I fuck with him. I want to work with him. I want to do a song with him. I think that could be pretty cool.

description.plain:
On “44 More,” Logic raps just one verse made out of precisely 44 bars. He talks about issues ranging from family troubles to doubters in the industry, while boasting his current position in the rap game.

The song is a sequel to Logic’s song “44 Bars” from his 2016 mixtape, Bobby Tarantino, which also features exactly 44 bars. This was confirmed by Visionary Music Group on Twitter prior to the song’s release.

“44 More” marks Logic’s first solo release since his third album Everybody back in 2017.

The song was teased on Logic’s Instagram story on his 28th birthday.

songs.title: Everybody

description.plain:
On “Everybody,”  Logic promotes racial equality, while interweaving his personal encounters with racism.

The song is Logic’s first release since his mixtape, Bobby Tarantino, which premiered eight months prior. He first teased the song on January 1, 2016 via Snapchat and Twitter and then during a Periscope in June.

songs.title: Under Pressure

description.plain:
Under Pressure’s title track was also its lead single, however, the single version was abbreviated to 3:50. Logic premiered the track during his While You Wait Tour, performing it during some of the shows.

Over a menacing beat composed of multiple samples, Logic cemented himself as one of the most notable young hip-hop talents with his steady wordplay and strong flow. The track was also self-produced, adding to how impressive this song is.

The official music video, which featured an alternate variation of the track, was premiered on October 9th. It was inspired by the Biting Elbows’s ‘'Bad Motherfucker’‘ music video—a fact Logic shared during an interview with DJ DUBL.

songs.title: Nikki

description.plain:
The identity of Nikki is finally revealed. In this song Logic struggles with his nicotine addiction which he refers to as Nikki; note the similarity of pronunciation – Nikki and nicotine. Logic understands that Nikki is not good for his health and is doing everything in his power to not go back with her, but lately Logic has been feeling like a slave for Nikki.



Logic goes by the nickname ‘Young Sinatra’ because his mom used to make him watch the legendary Frank Sinatra on TV when he was a child. Logic learned a lot from Mr. Sinatra and decided he wanted to bring that type of class to the hip-hop scene. However, Frank Sinatra was a known and common smoker. This could be one way that Logic was actually negatively influenced by his idol.

description.plain:
“Black Spiderman” is Logic’s way of telling people to be themselves and be proud of it and also to respect other people’s opinions.

He wants everyone to know that race, religion, color, creed, and sexual orientation shouldn’t be able to separate us because we are all human.

In the liner notes for this song, Logic said:

This song is the celebration of unity and a world built upon division. People say things like I don’t see color, I just see people. To which I retour you should see color, you should see a black man, a white woman, a brown little girl or any other color of the rainbow.

https://youtu.be/UFbLZpWgqtU#t=11m39s

This track features vocals from Damien Lemar Hudson.

Logic officially released this song on April 14th, 2017 as the second single from his third studio album Everybody.

This song was first teased on December 1, 2016 via Logic’s twitter:

https://twitter.com/logic301/status/804214871747280896

He also teased a part of it on his Instagram story:

https://youtu.be/XajUMduxh_8#t=2m53s

songs.title: 44 Bars

description.plain:
Logic spits precisely 44 bars detailing his struggles, pain, and determination to keep working hard for his fans and passion. The track notably samples Barrington Levy’s “The Vibes Is Right.”

According to Logic’s Snapchat story, “44 Bars” was recorded in 3 sessions over the course of 6 months in Los Angeles, Hawaii, and London.

In an interview with Hard Knock TV, Logic broke down the song. He originally planned to call it “2 Shades” or “Celebrate,” but scrapped the name. The second half of the song was recorded during the making of The Incredible True Story and was originally supposed to be similar to Eminem’s “Stan.”

songs.title: Flexicution

description.plain:
Flexicution is the combination of words “Flex” and “Execution”. It was created by Logic, who explained it on Twitter as: “a term and funny made up word for killing SHIT.”

The song is a braggadocious rap track filled with references to the recent success of Logic’s sophomore album, The Incredible True Story.

The outro is a duet between Logic and his wife at the time, Jessica Andrea, with John Lindahl contributing the male falsetto vocals.

Anticipation for the song began on April 5th 2016 when GFuel released an interview containing a teaser of his unreleased song, “Flexicution.” Since that day, fans have been demanding Logic #DropFlexicution. He went onto play the same snippets at various shows on his Incredible World Tour and teasing other snippets on his snapchat (Logic301) before finally dropping the track on June 13th 2016. He broke down the track’s creation during a Power 106 interview.

Logic also spoke about “Flexicution” in an interview with HardKnockTV.

He used a similar technique of splitting a song into two parts in “Paradise” from his sophomore album The Incredible True Story.

“Confessions of a Dangerous Mind” is the title track and second single from Logic’s sixth studio album.

Logic uses this song to vent feelings of insecurity that have been driven into his mind by living in the public eye. The constant comparison of his new and old works, along with the juxtaposition of his work to those of other popular artists, are conversed daily on the internet, leaving Logic, and other artists, with mental health issues.

body.plain:
“Confessions of a Dangerous Mind” is the title track and second single from Logic’s sixth studio album.

Logic uses this song to vent feelings of insecurity that have been driven into his mind by living in the public eye. The constant comparison of his new and old works, along with the juxtaposition of his work to those of other popular artists, are conversed daily on the internet, leaving Logic, and other artists, with mental health issues.

songs.title: Young Jesus

description.plain:
Logic joins forces with his RattPack crew mate Big Lenbo on this 90’s-esque track.

He took to Twitter on September 21st, 2015, a day before the track’s release, to announce the coming of “Young Jesus” – marking it as the lead single to his sophomore album, The Incredible True Story…

The track samples James Blake and RZA’s “Take a Fall For Me.” In an interview with Genius, Logic explained how RZA helped him clear the sample:


“I never met James Blake and he’s one of the most talented people in the world but he’s like a ghost. You can’t just reach James Blake, it’s insane. So the RZA hit me up to have dinner and this is the first time we ever met.

I went through RZA to contact James. RZA took out his phone right there and hit up James’ manager, “Bong Bong” was what he was saying."

songs.title: AfricAryaN

description.plain:
On “AfricAryaN,” Logic talks about his biracial background and the impact it has had on his life. He wants people to know that no matter what skin color they are, everybody is truly equal and comes from the same place.

Logic initially teased this track in an April 2016 interview with Rolling Stone, and then teased it again on “Studio Ambience At Night: Malibu,” a track from his 2016 mixtape, Bobby Tarantino. For the rest of 2016, he followed this up by with various snippets of the song all over his social media.

This track features a surprise feature from J. Cole, who is one of Logic’s biggest inspirations. There is also an appearance from Kai and Thomas from Logic’s second studio-album The Incredible True Story.

Everybody was initially supposed to share this song’s title.

description.plain:
“100 Miles and Running” is the first collaboration between DMV artists Logic and Wale.

The track’s title is a reference to Wale’s 2007 project 100 Miles and Running. The project was one of Wale’s more successful tapes, and Logic even used the same sample as its track, “W.A.L.E.D.A.N.C.E.” on his 2012 song “The Spotlight.”
https://twitter.com/Logic301/status/120919463003570176
Wale also teased this collaboration earlier in 2018 when he posted a snippet:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt-5yhQwZxc

100 Miles and Runnin' is also the title of an EP by N.W.A, it was the inspiration for Wale’s 2007 project.

In an interview with Hardknock TV, Logic revealed that this song was supposed to be on Ultra 85:
https://youtu.be/YxL_9DQWZVk?t=179

description.plain: This is the final song off the standard edition of Logic’s “Under Pressure” or the end of his Under Pressure Program – an exposition story element presented nearly at the end of every track throughout the album. “Till the End” is to be considered a closing chapter of the program where Logic’s struggles in successfully making it in the music industry, as well as improving – even slightly – relations with Nikki. This track taken as a whole – especially at the end – signals that this could be a revelation for Logic that, in some cases, has tads of Christian Hip Hop in it for its overall religious, or spiritual, tone.

description.plain:
On “Take It Back” Logic speaks mainly about his life experiences. He explains his childhood and how it made him become the person he is today.

Despite being subjected to racism and growing up in a negative environment, Logic persevered and carried his own to make it this far in life.

Logic also wants peace between all people and nothing else. At the end of the speech on this track, he says:

You can believe you’re superior. Fine. Just stop killing each other.

This song was initially teased on Logic’s Instagram story and then later teased on the album trailer and Bradley Martyn’s YouTube channel soon after.

He previously performed the track in London on July 5th, 2015 at Wireless Festival prior to its October 14th release. Check out this behind the scenes video about the making of the song.

The song is upbeat and meant to show how great things are going for Logic lately. After The Incredible True Story’s release, Logic sat with Genius and described the song.

“I never talked about the present on Under Pressure really and then this album is about the present and the future. So for me, this was the first joint that I was talking about me and where I am in my life and how cool shit is.”

Logic has also said that James Brown had inspired him to make this track.

songs.title: City of Stars

description.plain:
This is a break-up song dedicated to hip-hop where Logic details his relationship by personifying music as a woman.

The song starts off with a sample of Genesis' lead guitarist, Steve Hackett’s 1999 song “Days Of Long Ago.”

During the first half of the track, Logic sings with hurt in his voice, while using a hint of auto-tune. Musically the beginning of the song features a synth and drum line reminiscent of Kanye West’s “Flashing Lights.”

For the second half of the track, the beat switches and Logic uses rap bars to expresses his frustration with the music industry and his place in it.

“City of Stars” started out with an air of mystery; Logic used a similar songwriting approach on “Nikki”, where he rapped about his nicotine addiction.

After the song’s release fans questioned who Logic was addressing, he released a statement on Twitter, the day after his The Incredible True Story album dropped on November 13, 2015.

“It is a goodbye to ‘how a person should make hip hop’ and a hello ‘to finally embracing and focusing on Genre-less Music’,” he wrote to end all of the speculation.

songs.title: Anziety

description.plain:
“Anziety” is Logic’s depiction of what anxiety feels like. He shares his own story of his suffering so that people who feel the same way know they aren’t alone.

In a reply to a fan about anxiety, Logic tweeted:

https://twitter.com/logic301/status/853783021891198976

Anxiety is thought to be a villain in our lives, but Logic views it as a hero that makes us whole. We as humans need to experience highs and lows to truly live life to the fullest.

The title comes from a mistake that 6ix, the producer of this track made when titling the beat which he confirmed via Twitter:

https://twitter.com/6ixvmg/status/860364095937159168

This track was initially teased on December 2, 2016 via Logic’s Twitter:

https://twitter.com/logic301/status/804850184979156993

“Wu-Tang Forever” is a special collaboration between Logic and every member of the Wu-Tang Clan except for Ol' Dirty Bastard, who tragically passed away in 2004.

The Wu-Tang Clan were instrumental during the beginning of Logic’s career, so this collaboration brings everything full circle. He spoke to HardKnockTV back in 2013 and explained that he found RZA through the Kill Bill Volume 1 Original Soundtrack and that opened him up to the key ‘90s hip-hop influencers.

Logic announced this collaboration in an Instagram story after word started getting out from fans who joined him in Los Angeles for a private listening party:
https://twitter.com/LinesofLogic/status/1041525333546205184

songs.title: Warm It Up

description.plain:
On “Warm It Up,” Logic revives his Young Sinatra persona. This persona was last seen on “Ice Cold” during his feature where he rapped:

Livin' on the need to get down but I digress
Young Sinatra on the track
Throw it back and nevertheless

This song is filled with references to many of Logic’s old songs, such as “Live on the Air” and “Intro.”. Ironically, Logic has distinguished a difference between his two alter egos – Young Sinatra and Bobby Tarantino. In an interview with Hardknocktv, he says in reference to Bobby Tarantino:

It’s not Logic. It’s not Young Sinatra. It’s Bobby Tarantino. Bobby Tarantino is the alter ego of me, and Bobby Tarantino is just the turn up, fun.

description.plain:
“Killing Spree” is Logic’s way of questioning our society and its misuse of social media and technology.

On his track “Flexicution,” Logic rapped:

Bitch, put down your camera and live in the moment.

Logic is trying to explain in this track that we need to embrace reality and make our lives about experiences instead of technology and social media.

In a Verified interview with Genius, Logic commented on the songs meaning:

This song very simply is about social media, straight up and the things that we glorify and focus on in social media.

This song also features background vocals from Logic’s ex-wife Jessica Andrea.

The first verse off of this track was performed during Logic’s While You Wait tour and also in the 2nd episode of The Boombox’s YouTube series of “16 Bars”

Logic also performed this track on The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon.

description.plain:
“Indica Badu” is an anthem explaining the beauty of smoking weed, featuring Wiz Khalifa, who’s known to be an avid smoker of marijuana. Relating to the vibe smoking weed gives off, the vibe of the instrumental is very chill and resembles how someone would feel on a high. The song also ends in exactly 4:20, a number used to represent weed and smoking.

The title “Indica Badu” derives from the combination of Cannabis Indica aka marijuana and Erykah Badu, an American singer-songwriter, record producer, disc jockey, activist, and actress and is recognized as being one of the most legendary female artists of all time. This combination assists in the theme of the song that weed is amazing.

One reason that this song is very chill and resembles how someone would feel on a high is because it uses the drum pattern as “Metropolis,” which was sampled from “Use Me” by Bill Withers. The same sample is also used on Kendrick Lamar’s “Sing About Me, I’m Dying of Thirst.”

This song seems to have been in the works for a while, as Wiz first teased the collab back in December in this tweet:
https://twitter.com/wizkhalifa/status/938849566778048512?s=21

In turn, Pusha T details the effect of that cocaine trickling into the hands of a young man presumably himself in the American projects whom in return, is distributing it as crack.

description.plain:
In the title track (and final track) of The Incredible True Story, Logic closes out his album and completes the frame narrative of his album.

The track is a three-verse song, followed by an excerpt from an Alan Watts speech called “What If Money Was No Object?”, followed by a dialogue between William Kai and Quentin Thomas as they finally arrive on the planet Paradise.

The common theme throughout the three elements is that people should focus on doing what they desire in life—Logic does this through his music, Watts urges people to find their own art, and Kai and Thomas literally seek life itself in the form of a new planet.

“The Incredible True Story” refers to the story of Logic’s life, which is legendary in this fictional future (100 years from now). In this song, the full title, “The Incredible True Story
And Transformation of the Man Who Saved the World” is finally revealed.

Logic had previously promoted it as “TITSATOTMWSTW.”

In “Yuck,” Logic is rapping to those that have beef with him. He explains that he never responds to rappers that come at him because he doesn’t have to, he lets his success talk.

This track may also be a subliminal shot at Joyner Lucas, addressing the “beef” between the two; even though Logic hasn’t actually named him in a track. Logic has denied these claims, stating he’d say someone’s name if it was a diss track.

songs.title: Slave II

description.plain:
“Slave II” is a proclamation by Logic that he deserves to be in this position of the rap game. He contrasts his life from struggling in poverty, to signing a record deal and performing for the masses.

The song’s beat is an alternated version of Bryson Tiller’s “Rambo” due to complications with Def Jam. The song goes in-depth about Logic’s state in the game and feeling like a slave, or worker, for hip-hop and the expectations of others. Logic’s own hit, “Nikki”, is sampled—a song about another type of slavery: addiction.

The fact that “Slave II” comes before “Slave” on the mixtape could be an allusion to Quentin Tarantino’s non-linear storytelling in his movie Pulp Fiction.

songs.title: Overnight

description.plain:
On “Overnight,” Logic describes the way many people falsely believe that he became famous overnight. He then goes on to explain why this belief is incorrect and says that it took years of hard work and dedication to get to where he is now.

The song is the second one to be released by Logic in 2018, dropping just four days after his track “44 More.”

The track was first released as a music video that was mostly recorded during Logic’s trips to Japan and Maui, while other parts of it were recorded on a plane.

This song was first teased on Logic’s Snapchat story on February 28th, 2017, almost exactly one year prior to the song’s release. When asked about the release of the teased snippet, Logic responded on Twitter that it was never coming out.

songs.title: YSIV

description.plain:
The title track to Logic’s fourth studio album shares some recurring samples with its predecessors, “Young Sinatra II” and “Young Sinatra III,” most notably Nas‘ 1994 track “Life’s a Bitch” and Miilkbone’s 1995 track “Keep it Real.”

The first verse incorporates a slightly altered and more precise version of “YSIV Freestyle,” which Logic initially used to announce the album and its release date.

Following Mac Miller’s unfortunate passing on September 7, 2018, Logic added a brief intro and an extended outro dedicated to Miller. In the outro, he revealed that Mac inspired him to “start doing this Young Sinatra shit.”



Logic’s second verse on the 2015 song “Innermission” was originally deemed “Young Sinatra IV” by Logic himself, but there was never an official release of this verse separate from the original song.

description.plain:
“Young Sinatra III” is the third song in a tetralogy to use the ‘Young Sinatra’ name.

Similar to the first and second, Logic spits about the style of his flow and how it continues to earn him more praise in the music industry.

Including this track, each song in the trilogy samples the hook from “Life’s A Bitch” by Nas and AZ.

songs.title: Hallelujah

description.plain:
Logic uses “Hallelujah” to open up Everybody by giving his take on the world. This album is not purely from his perspective, but he wanted to warm everyone up and set the stage using his own thoughts.

The skit at the end of this track begins the concept behind the album, where Atom is walking home and gets killed as a car hits him. He then meets God, who is in charge of leading him into his next life.

This track features vocals from Patrick Starr.

It was initially teased on Logic’s Instagram story:

https://youtu.be/XajUMduxh_8#t=3m20s
